{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01R2iRiuzPJJyUyjtGXip5D1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! `kubernetes.default.svc.cluster.local` resolves correctly, and `es-http.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` resolves to the ClusterIP. But `es-headless.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local` fails with NXDOMAIN.\n\nThe headless service `es-headless` has `clusterIP: None` - this means it should still have DNS entries but they point to the individual pod IPs, not a VIP. However, the DNS entries for a headless service only show up once the pods are Ready (have a pod IP and pass readiness probes). Since none of the pods are Ready yet, the headless service DNS doesn't have any A records.\nThis creates a chicken-and-egg problem: the pods need to discover each other through DNS to bootstrap the cluster, but DNS won't resolve until the pods are Ready, which requires the cluster to already be formed. I need to figure out how to break this cycle.\n\nThe solution is to use the stable pod DNS names directly instead of relying on the service DNS. In a StatefulSet, each pod gets a predictable DNS name based on its ordinal index, so I can configure the discovery seeds to point to those individual pod names rather than the headless service. These names should resolve to the pod IPs even before the pods become Ready, which would let them bootstrap the cluster. Let me verify whether the headless service actually registers pod IPs in its Endpoints before the readiness probe passes.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":418,"cache_read_input_tokens":41500,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":418},"output_tokens":45,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"1811e6eb-b38e-40db-943